name: Tachyglossus aculeatus
occurrenceRemarks: Sighting and photos (c) arisc. Field Notes - I felt a bit bad for this echidna. It was found around mid-afternoon in a field that we were camping in during the week leading up to a music festival to be held there, and I dare say it usually lives in the area in peace (at least since the end of the festival in the same location a year before). It seemed to be trying to find its way under this tent, skirting around the edges as though looking for a way in. I wasnt sure if perhaps it had a hole down there, or perhaps the tent was over a particularly tasty ants nest - there were a lot of ants and ant neats around, thats for sure! Anyway, we got the professionals to relocate it because we figured displacement was a better option than it potentially getting run over when the 20,000 or so festval-goers would arrive a couple of days later. Lesser of two evils? Anyway, it was a pretty big echidna at maybe close to 50cm in length if I were to estimate. I hope its doing okay at this point and will eventually find its way safely back after the festival is done with.

name: Petaurus norfolcensis
occurrenceRemarks: Sighting and photos (c) hanna_coffey. Field Notes - For the last 3 nights ive been recieving visits from this very special creature, shes been raiding an old mealworm farm. I was worried about her as she was alone and it seemed unusual she would risk coming near a human - but the drought has been very hard on all our beautiful wildlide and everyone is hungry. Just to be sure, I took this photo and contacted a friend who is a glider expert (the glider coordinator of the wildlife rescue i volunteer for). She confirmed that it is in fact a squirrel glider, gave me some good advice, and told me to keep an eye on it - last night she was back again but this time with a couple of friends! I was so happy to see that she was ok and still with her social group - a very good sign. Was such an enormous gift to get to see these guys up close and wild.
